params.text: The dataset consists of `products` and there is an edge between two products if they are frequently `bought together`. We will train our PyKEEN model to embed this graph as accurately as it is able to and then downstream we will an MLP capable of recommending two items to be bought together, using features obtained from a 'bag of words' embedding of the specific product.
## This is a demo demonstrating how can we use embeddings obtained from PyKEEN models in other downstream tasks.

Here we define our model that will learn the graph structure and store it in embeddings, that we will extract later. 

For more information about graph embedding models check out the `Link Prediction with PyKEEN`demo.
As most PyKEEN workflows require validation sets on top of the normal training and testing sets, we need to split our dataset into 3.

This box will train the model to learn the given graph, with your normal options of training, testing and validation sets, optimizer type, loss function and epochs.

Training approach is a graph embedding model special option, more about the two options in the `Link Prediction with PyKEEN` demo.

This is where the magic happens. We need to extract the learned embeddings from the model, it can be done with this one easy box.

PyKEEN models might have multiple embeddings. For example the KG2E model has 2 embeddings one for mean and other for diagonal covariance, as this model is quite special and interprets entities and relations as probability distributions. 

This box extracts all embeddings into their own tables so downstream tasks can easily choose between what embedding they use, or just concatenate them all and use it that way.

Here are the embedding models performance metrics. It managed to learn and recall the graph with a 78% accuracy and a 43% precision, these are not the best results, however using these embeddings already lead to a great improvement in downstream tasks. With an even better model that could learn the graph structure better, we would most likely see great results in more complicated downstream tasks.

Here we load and prepare the data from the products feature vectors, the format is the following for this particular demo: `node_id` is a number, and `feature_vector` is a python list, but you could just have `node_id, feature_1, feature_2, ...` and just concatenate all of them in a different box.
Also rename the columns to the expected `node_label`, as the extraction is in `node_label, embedding` format
This box performs simple concatenation for all entities/nodes.

In graph embedding we usually only have positive samples, the edges of the graph. But for learning we will also need negative samples. This box just chooses two nodes that are not connected in the original graph and adds them with a negative label. The strategy here is random, but with the editing of this box, or possibly already having negative samples from outer sources the MLP models performance might increase.

Here is just the normal PyTorch `Define model` box. We have defined a basic 3 layer MLP model, that takes embeddings and features concatenates them. Does a simple Linear function on both of them separately then adds the result together for order invariance. And 2 more linear layers follow with a final sigmoid activation output layer, and a binary cross-entropy loss.

Here we could replace this box with any model that takes embeddings and features and do anything with this data, and we would have to change very little about the workflow. That is the power of LynxKite.
For training we need to split the positive and negative samples into training and testing sets with this simple box here.

Here we will train our basic MLP model with the `Train model` box that is in basic LynxKite. Assign the correct columns to the correct inputs, set the epochs and a batch size, and the training can start like in normal machine learning tasks.

This is where we can see that the model learned our dataset quite well with little learning time (granted this dataset is small at ~5k edges) and that the accuracy and precision of this model trained on the embeddings and features outclass our just embeddings learning PyKEEN model.

Here we corrupt the original data by permuting it. With this we can easily see that our model did actually learn the structure of the data and the correlation with features quite well, and it did not just find some shortcut. As these results are close to the model basically randomly guessing (as it should because the data is nonsensical).

Key takeaways

- Strong baseline performance: High precision with somewhat lower recall (conservative positives), overall `F1 0.935`.
- Embeddings carry the bulk of the signal: Permuting embeddings collapses performance to near-random (`F1 0.482`; `-0.453` absolute, -48% vs baseline). 
- Input features still help but are secondary: Permuting features degrades performance, but the model remains decent (`F1 0.779`; `-0.157` absolute, -17% vs baseline). This retains about 83% of the F1.
- Corrupting both ≈ corrupting embeddings alone: `F1 0.477` vs `F1 0.482`, reinforcing that embeddings dominate predictive power.
